research comparative medicine stanford university school of medicine stanford school of medicine comparative medicine search this site only stanford medical sites ways to give find a person alumni lane library ways to give find a person the comparative approach to research and discovery the concept of one medicine one health is based upon a fundamental idea advances in both human and veterinary medicine are dependent on overlapping technologies and research discoveries this is the essence of comparative medicine the study of the close connections between human and animal health and disease the faculty in the department of comparative medicine are basic researchers or veterinary clinician scientists all working toward one health basic scientist faculty use animal models of epilepsy neuronal reorganization and recovery after injury and cortical neuronal circuitry to study physiological and patho physiological processes the veterinary clinical faculty in the department of comparative medicine research interests focus on topics pertaining to laboratory animal and wildlife health and on animal models of human disease the species studied are diverse ranging from rodents to the african clawed frog see the faculty's abstracts by clicking on their image the laboratory xenopus book cover lab animal journal cover of a fat tailed jird cell journal cover image journal of anatomy cover photo of elephant journal of experimental medicine cover image science of translational research cover image you are here stanford medicine school of medicine departments comparative medicine research navigation for this section research overview labs megan albertelli paul buckmaster donna bouley corinna darian smith stephen felt joseph garner sherril green shaul hestrin jennifer johns claude nagamine cholawat pacharinsak navigation for this section related links veterinary service center administrative panel on laboratory animal care site navigation home education overview courses in comparative m